<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Adults of this new species are easily separated from other members of the species group by their yellowish brown elytra bearing longitudinal brown stripes and modified tarsi of the middle leg. In addition, some putative autapomorphies are found in genitalic characters, including the characteristic shape of the aedeagus and single endophallic sclerite bearing teeth near the apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta tahsiangi sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E abdominal ventrite VIII F apex of tibia of middle leg, male G spermatheca H tarsi of middle leg, male I abdominal ventrite V, female J abdominal ventrite V, male K gonocoxae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545540" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10C</figureCitation>
). The truncate apex of abdominal ventrite VIII in females is also diagnostic (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta tahsiangi sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E abdominal ventrite VIII F apex of tibia of middle leg, male G spermatheca H tarsi of middle leg, male I abdominal ventrite V, female J abdominal ventrite V, male K gonocoxae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545540" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10E</figureCitation>
) (tapering apex of abdominal ventrite VIII in females of others).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
